  "answer": "**No work in the corpus directly addresses the question of \"how the past should bind the present\" as a central theme.** However, several works engage indirectly with related concepts, particularly the tension between inherited traditions (past laws, customs, doctrines) and present obligations or natural rights. These fall into two categories:\n\n### Indic Smṛti Texts (Dharma Literature)\nThese ancient legal/moral treatises define *Dharma* (law, duty, righteousness) through sources rooted in the past: **Śruti** (revealed Veda), **Smṛti** (\"remembered\" traditions of sages), customs (*ācāra*) of the virtuous (*sadācāra*), and practices of the good. They bind the present via ancestral authority, but allow flexibility through conscience or local custom—implying the past *informs* but does not rigidly dictate the present.[^1][^2][^3][^4][^5]\n\n- **Manusmṛti** (primary engagement): Dharma's \"root-source\" is Veda/Smṛti, virtuous conduct, and self-satisfaction; past traditions guide but conflict resolution favors learned virtuous consensus.[^6]\n- **Kātyāyana Smṛti**: References \"local custom\" (*deśācāra*) validating documents/rites; weighs Śruti, procedure, custom, royal edicts.[^7]\n- **Nāradasmṛti**, **Bṛhaspati Smṛti**, **Aṅgirasa Smṛti**, etc.: Invoke precedents (*pūrva*), virtuous customs; disputes resolved by \"proclaimed virtuous\" testimony.[^8]\n\nThese treat the past (Smṛti/customs) as authoritative yet contextual, not absolute—engaging binding via tradition vs. present equity.\n\n### Charles Comte's Works (Critique of Inherited Doctrines)\nComte argues ancient slave-owning doctrines (Roman jurists, feudal customs) improperly *bind* modern free societies, distorting property/liberty. Past jurisprudence (e.g., slavery-based rights) must yield to natural laws observed in present facts.[^9][^10]\n\n- **Traité de Législation (Vols. I–IV)**: Critiques systems where past \"natural laws\" (Roman/Grotius) or conventions bind present; urges analytical method over inherited errors.[^11]\n- **Traité de la Propriété (Vols. I–II)**: Past slave doctrines corrupt modern property ideas; liberty rejects ancestral binding.[^12]\n\n**Honest assessment**: The corpus (37 works) lacks comprehensive treatment; Smṛtis affirm past traditions/customs as Dharma sources (binding via virtuous practice), Comte rejects past errors binding present liberty. No explicit philosophical debate (e.g., Burke vs. revolutionaries). Topics like precedent in law appear tangentially.[^13]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Ch. 2, [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-d70b97].\n[^2]: Ibid., [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-608b3f].\n[^3]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-58c5ff].\n[^4]: Aṅgirasa Smṛti, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-4c73fa].\n[^5]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 4, [/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/04/translation/#p-44d48b].\n[^6]: Manusmṛti, Ch. 2 (full), [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/].\n[^7]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, multiple chs., e.g., Ch. 25 [/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/25/translation/#p-f61337]; Ch. 53 [/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/53/translation/#p-4e9200].\n[^8]: Nāradasmṛti, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-3ff7ac].\n[^9]: Traité de Législation I, Ch. 1, [/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/01/translation/].\n[^10]: Ibid., Ch. 5, [/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/05/translation/#p-ed7762].\n[^11]: Ibid., Chs. 5–8 (full critique of past systems), [/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/05/translation/].\n[^12]: Traité de la Propriété I, Preface/Ch. 1, [/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/00-preface/translation/#p-a65ce7]; [/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/01/translation/#p-1295cf].\n[^13]: E.g., minor refs. in Dunoyer (customs' influence), but no deep engagement.",
